[1]
Date: 18 Feb 2005
From: Doris Gabel <Doris.Gabel@dso.de>
Source: DSQ (Deutsche Stifung Organtransplantation, Press release,
Wed 16 Feb 2005] [edited]

Rabies Transmission Through Organ Donation
------------------------------------------
Great precautions are taken to avoid disease transmission through
transplantation, but a small risk always remains: 3 patients in
Germany may have caught rabies through an organ donation from a
deceased woman who was probably infected with the disease. The
Deutsche Stiftung Organtransplantation (DSO, German Organ
Transplantation Foundation; Federal Organ Procurement Agency) regrets
that this could have happened, although all necessary care has been
taken, and the donor underwent all medically indicated examinations
before her organs were removed.
In Neu-Isenburg the DSO announces that 3 patients suspected of having
rabies may have been infected through organ transplants (lungs,
combined kidney/pancreas, and kidney) performed in 3 German
transplant centers (Hanover, Marburg, Hannovers Muenden) at the end
of 2004. These 3 recipients have been hospitalized with suspected
rabies and are in extremely critical condition. 3 other patients who
received the liver and the corneas from the same donor and who were
transplanted in Heidelberg and Mainz are well.
The organ donor had no symptoms of rabies. She was a young woman who
was hospitalized in December 2004. She suffered a cardiac arrest that
led to brain death due to a lack of oxygen despite resuscitation
measures that transiently stabilized her circulation.
"This has never happened before in Germany," said Professor Guenter
Kirste from the Board of the DSO. "We know of a case of rabies
transmission via organ donation that occurred in the USA last summer.
Unfortunately, such rare infections cannot be excluded beforehand in
the organ donation process despite rigorous donor screening
procedures. A small degree of risk through rare infections is always
present in organ transplantation." He also emphasized that this
[regrettable] case should not [cause us to] forget that organ
transplants are a well-established therapeutic option with undoubted
benefits that by far outweigh the risks.
Tests to confirm the diagnosis of rabies in the organ donor are
currently under way in the rabies laboratory of the Institute of
Virology of Essen University Medical Center and at the Bernhard Nocht
Institute for Tropical Medicine in Hamburg.
Rabies is typically transmitted to humans through bites of an
infected animal. Transmission through skin injuries or through direct
contact with the infectious material (such as saliva) with mucous
membranes is also possible. Anecdotal cases of human-to-human
transmission through transplantation are documented -- but no such
case has occurred in Germany before. As a precaution, all staff
members of the transplant centers, the hospitals, and the DSO who
were involved in the organ donation process and potentially exposed
to rabies through contact with the donor and the recipients received
active and passive immunization.
"The risk of catching rabies in Germany is very low," said Dr. Andrea
Koch, head of the Department of Infectious Epidemiology of the Robert
Koch Institute in Berlin. The last 2 deaths from rabies in Germany
occurred in 1996 and 2004, and both patients caught the disease
abroad. Usually, all individuals assumed to have been exposed to an
animal infected with rabies are vaccinated, which successfully
prevents the onset of the disease. Information on rabies can be found
at: <http://www.rki.de/INFEKT/INFEKT.HTM>.
--
Ilja Stracke, Head of Communications
Deutsche Stiftung Organtransplantation
Emil von Behring-Passage
63263 Neu-Isenburg, Germany
<presse@dso.de>
