[2]
Date Fri 18 Feb 2005
From: Doris Gabel <Doris.Gabel@dso.de>
Source: DSQ (Deutsche Stifung Organtransplantation, Press release, 17
Feb 2005 [edited]

Suspected rabies transmission through organ donation confirmed
--------------------------------------------------------------
The Institute of Virology in Essen and Bernhard Nocht Institute for
Tropical Medicine in Hamburg confirm diagnosis of rabies in organ
donor
The Deutsche Stiftung Organ-transplantation (DSO, German Organ
Transplantation Foundation; Federal Organ Procurement Agency)
confirms that the organ donor whose organs were transplanted into 6
patients in Germany early in 2005 actually had rabies. The
preliminary diagnosis was confirmed by histological and immunological
tests performed in brain tissue from the donor at the Bernhard Nocht
Institute for Tropical Medicine. "There is no doubt about the
diagnosis," said Professor Dr. Herbert Schmitz, head of the
Department of Virology of the Bernhard Nocht Institute, "the tissue
specimens examined yielded definitive evidence." This was also
confirmed by the head of the Institute of Virology, Professor Dr.
Michael Roggendorf.
In 2 of the patients who received organs from this donor, the rabies
virus was isolated by means of molecular biological tests. It is thus
obvious that these recipients have been infected. In another
recipient, the neutralization test identified rabies-specific
antibodies. This result may also be due to an earlier exposure to the
virus and thus does not provide clear-cut evidence of an acute rabies
infection.
Regrets were expressed by Professor Dr. Guenter Kirste, Board of the
DSO. He also emphasized that despite the public concern about this
case, "the anonymity of the donor and her relatives must be strictly
preserved. We must not forget that organ donation is a generous gift
and that the donor is definitely not to blame for this unfortunate
situation."
--
Ilja Stracke, Head of Communications
Deutsche Stiftung Organtransplantation
Emil von Behring-Passage
63263 Neu-Isenburg, Germany
<presse@dso.de>
