[3]
Date: Fri 18 Feb 2005
From: Helmut Fickenscher <Helmut.Fickenscher@med.uni-heidelberg.de>

Transplant-mediated rabies infection
-------------------------------------
[A statement communicated by Prof. Helmut Fickenscher, on behalf of
M. Buechler, J. Encke, H. Fickenscher, H. Geiss, T. Kraus, P. Sauer,
J. Schmidt, W. Stremmel, J. Werner, University of Heidelberg; M.
Roggendorf, R.S. Ross, B. Wolters, University of Essen; and T.
Mueller, Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut, Wusterhausen].

As reported previously [see: Rabies, human, organ transplantation -
Germany 20050217.0530], a transplant donor whose death had been
attributed to acute cerebral ischemia has now been identified to have
been infected with rabies. On 1 Jan 2005, and during several days
thereafter, 6 patients received transplants of kidney,
kidney/pancreas, lung, liver, and corneas, respectively. Whereas the
patients with kidney, pancreas, and lung transplants developed
encephalitis within 6 weeks, the cornea patients and the patient with
liver transplantation at the University Hospital in Heidelberg are
clinically doing fine.
Immediately after the information about the probable rabies infection
of the donor reached us, the liver transplant recipient was
readmitted in the early morning of 15 Feb 2005, and a combined
active/passive rabies immunization was administered. On the same day,
a combination therapy with ribavirin and pegylated interferon was
started. The diagnostic procedures have been performed at the
National Reference Center for Rabies at the University of Essen and
the OIE Reference Laboratory for Rabies at Wusterhausen, Germany.
Surprisingly, high levels of anti-rabies antibodies have been
detected by both ELISA and neutralization tests and the specificity
was confirmed by western blot analysis. Initial tests for nucleic
acids have been negative up to now.
Thus, whereas 3 other patients are in critical condition, the liver
transplant patient at Heidelberg Medical Center appears to be
protected from rabies. There are anamnestic hints that the patient
may have received a rabies vaccination in childhood. It is
conceivable that the transplantation of the rabies-infected liver may
have boosted this preexisting immune response, producing high titers
of neutralizing antibodies. This hypothesis is currently being
checked by testing a pre-transplantation serum sample.
--
Prof. Dr. Helmut Fickenscher
Abteilung Virologie, Hygiene-Institut
Im Neuenheimer Feld 324
D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany
<helmut.fickenscher@med.uni-heidelberg.de>
